25
00:02:08,050 --> 00:02:12,072
You had said you would take a ten-day vacation so I just assumed you would be travelling abroad.

26
00:02:12,072 --> 00:02:13,006
 

27
00:02:13,006 --> 00:02:15,076
But you are headed for Yamagata, Okajima-san [Miss Okajima]?

28
00:02:15,076 --> 00:02:15,078
 

29
00:02:15,078 --> 00:02:16,080
Yes.

30
00:02:16,080 --> 00:02:16,082
 

31
00:02:16,082 --> 00:02:18,060
Did you break up with someone...?

32
00:02:18,060 --> 00:02:20,045
 

33
00:02:20,045 --> 00:02:22,009
I yearn for the countryside.

34
00:02:22,009 --> 00:02:22,018
 

35
00:02:22,018 --> 00:02:22,097
`Bye!

36
00:02:22,097 --> 00:02:22,097
 

37
00:02:22,097 --> 00:02:23,070
See you later!

38
00:02:23,070 --> 00:02:23,070
 

39
00:02:23,070 --> 00:02:25,012
Let's go to Hama's house.

40
00:02:25,012 --> 00:02:25,012
 

41
00:02:25,012 --> 00:02:26,002
Nyah, nyah!

42
00:02:26,002 --> 00:02:26,002
 

43
00:02:26,002 --> 00:02:27,098
What do you mean, ``Nyah'' ?!

44
00:02:27,098 --> 00:02:28,066
 

45
00:02:28,066 --> 00:02:29,056
Let's go, let's go!

46
00:02:29,056 --> 00:02:29,056
 

47
00:02:29,056 --> 00:02:31,003
So...did your grades go up?

48
00:02:31,003 --> 00:02:31,003
 

49
00:02:31,003 --> 00:02:31,097
Uh-uh.

50
00:02:31,097 --> 00:02:33,007
 

51
00:02:33,007 --> 00:02:34,015
But it's all right.

52
00:02:34,015 --> 00:02:34,026
 

53
00:02:34,026 --> 00:02:34,096
How come?

54
00:02:34,096 --> 00:02:34,098
 

55
00:02:34,098 --> 00:02:40,066
As soon as I get home, we're going to Grandma's house.  So I won't be in trouble until much later.

56
00:02:40,066 --> 00:02:40,066
 

57
00:02:40,066 --> 00:02:42,020
Wow, that's nice.

58
00:02:42,020 --> 00:02:42,047
 

59
00:02:42,047 --> 00:02:43,097
Toko-chan, are you going to the country, too?

60
00:02:43,097 --> 00:02:44,016
 

61
00:02:44,016 --> 00:02:46,097
Yeah, to Nagano.  Are you, Taeko-chan?

62
00:02:46,097 --> 00:02:46,097
 

63
00:02:46,097 --> 00:02:48,004
I'm not sure.

64
00:02:48,004 --> 00:02:48,004
 

65
00:02:48,004 --> 00:02:50,084
Well, guess what--my father bought a cabin!

66
00:02:50,084 --> 00:02:50,093
 

67
00:02:50,093 --> 00:02:52,084
Wow, that's great!

68
00:02:52,084 --> 00:02:54,035
 

69
00:02:54,035 --> 00:02:57,030
As I expected, your math grade's not good.

70
00:02:57,030 --> 00:02:58,014
 

71
00:02:58,014 --> 00:03:03,090
Yeah, but I got a ``B'' in science.  Oh, Mom?  Are we going somewhere for vacation?

72
00:03:03,090 --> 00:03:03,090
 

73
00:03:03,090 --> 00:03:05,024
Nowhere special.

74
00:03:05,024 --> 00:03:05,086
 

75
00:03:05,086 --> 00:03:07,090
Hey, Mom, take me someplace.

76
00:03:07,090 --> 00:03:08,080
 

77
00:03:08,080 --> 00:03:13,034
I'll take you to a movie. "Tsuru No Ongaeshi" [<The Crane's Return>] is playing, isn't it?

78
00:03:13,034 --> 00:03:13,054
 

79
00:03:13,054 --> 00:03:16,052
That's not what I meant--someplace in the country.

80
00:03:16,052 --> 00:03:16,054
 

81
00:03:16,054 --> 00:03:17,052
The country?

82
00:03:17,052 --> 00:03:17,052
 

83
00:03:17,052 --> 00:03:20,002
Right, like ``Grandma's house in the country''.

84
00:03:20,002 --> 00:03:20,008
 

85
00:03:20,008 --> 00:03:21,064
Your Grandmother lives here, doesn't she?

86
00:03:21,064 --> 00:03:21,064
 

87
00:03:21,064 --> 00:03:22,050
Then Grandpa!

88
00:03:22,050 --> 00:03:22,050
 

89
00:03:22,050 --> 00:03:27,052
Didn't he pass away?  We don't know any places in the country.  Please don't ask for something we can't possibly do.

90
00:03:27,052 --> 00:03:32,050
 

91
00:03:32,050 --> 00:03:39,098
I was born and raised in Tokyo, and my parents were as well. I always envied my friends who had a country hometown to return to.

92
00:03:39,098 --> 00:03:42,062
 

93
00:03:42,062 --> 00:03:45,076
It's impossible to take a trip now, because everywhere will be crowded.

94
00:03:45,076 --> 00:03:45,078
 

95
00:03:45,078 --> 00:03:47,060
But I want to go somewhere.

96
00:03:47,060 --> 00:03:48,056
 

97
00:03:48,056 --> 00:03:49,072
How about Ohnohya?

98
00:03:49,072 --> 00:03:49,076
 

99
00:03:49,076 --> 00:03:50,052
Huh?

100
00:03:50,052 --> 00:03:50,054
 

101
00:03:50,054 --> 00:03:54,066
We've been regular visitors, so if we chose to go to Ohnohya, we might be able to reserve a room.

102
00:03:54,066 --> 00:03:54,066
 

103
00:03:54,066 --> 00:03:56,010
Where, where is it?

104
00:03:56,010 --> 00:03:56,012
 

105
00:03:56,012 --> 00:03:59,044
Oh, sure--Ohnohya is good, because Taeko hasn't been there before.

106
00:03:59,044 --> 00:03:59,046
 

107
00:03:59,046 --> 00:04:00,076
Say, that's right...

108
00:04:00,076 --> 00:04:00,078
 

109
00:04:00,078 --> 00:04:03,032
Hey, is it in the mountains?  By the sea?

110
00:04:03,032 --> 00:04:03,032
 

111
00:04:03,032 --> 00:04:05,018
It's the Atami hot springs.

112
00:04:05,018 --> 00:04:05,018
 

113
00:04:05,018 --> 00:04:07,072
Huh--``Atami''?

114
00:04:07,072 --> 00:04:07,074
 

115
00:04:07,074 --> 00:04:10,022
Right.  You can reach it by bullet train.

116
00:04:10,022 --> 00:04:10,024
 

117
00:04:10,024 --> 00:04:12,068
Oh, sure, that place would be good.

118
00:04:12,068 --> 00:04:16,038
 

119
00:04:16,038 --> 00:04:17,050
Atami...

120
00:04:17,050 --> 00:04:17,052
 

121
00:04:17,052 --> 00:04:20,046
It's really fun--there are all kinds of baths.

122
00:04:20,046 --> 00:04:20,048
 

123
00:04:20,048 --> 00:04:23,056
Um, yeah, there's a giant Roman Bath.

124
00:04:23,056 --> 00:04:23,058
 

125
00:04:23,058 --> 00:04:29,062
That's right, and many smaller ones like the Swan Bath and the Pansy Bath.

126
00:04:29,062 --> 00:04:29,062
 

127
00:04:29,062 --> 00:04:31,070
Right, right!  The Pansy Bath!

128
00:04:31,070 --> 00:04:32,034
 

129
00:04:32,034 --> 00:04:33,072
Pansy Bath?

130
00:04:33,072 --> 00:04:33,074
 

131
00:04:33,074 --> 00:04:36,010
Yeah, it's a really fantastic bath!

132
00:04:36,010 --> 00:04:36,012
 

133
00:04:36,012 --> 00:04:38,018
Taeko, you just love baths, don't you?

134
00:04:38,018 --> 00:04:38,054
 

135
00:04:38,054 --> 00:04:42,086
Okay, well Father is working and can't go, so why don't you four go together?

136
00:04:42,086 --> 00:04:42,088
 

137
00:04:42,088 --> 00:04:44,026
Huh?

138
00:04:44,026 --> 00:04:47,078
 

139
00:04:47,078 --> 00:04:48,092
US...

140
00:04:48,092 --> 00:04:48,094
 

141
00:04:48,094 --> 00:04:50,010
...go TOO?

142
00:04:50,010 --> 00:04:50,010
 

143
00:04:50,010 --> 00:04:57,036
1,2,3,4,5,6...lean to the side...

144
00:04:57,036 --> 00:04:57,036
 

145
00:04:57,036 --> 00:05:00,060
Taeko-chan, it's incredible--you've come to every single radio exercise.

146
00:05:00,060 --> 00:05:01,036
 

147
00:05:01,036 --> 00:05:03,060
Well, everyone else has gone to the countryside, after all.

148
00:05:03,060 --> 00:05:05,076
 

149
00:05:05,076 --> 00:05:07,098
Taeko-chan, aren't you going anywhere?

150
00:05:07,098 --> 00:05:08,064
 

151
00:05:08,064 --> 00:05:09,046
I'm going!

152
00:05:09,046 --> 00:05:09,046
 

153
00:05:09,046 --> 00:05:10,010
Where?

154
00:05:10,010 --> 00:05:10,012
 

155
00:05:10,012 --> 00:05:11,042
Atami!

156
00:05:11,042 --> 00:05:11,044
 

157
00:05:11,044 --> 00:05:14,062
Atami?  What are you going to Atami for?

158
00:05:14,062 --> 00:05:14,064
 

159
00:05:14,064 --> 00:05:16,010
To go bathing!

160
00:05:16,010 --> 00:05:17,083
 

161
00:05:17,083 --> 00:05:19,026
Ohhh?

162
00:05:19,026 --> 00:05:20,038
 

163
00:05:20,038 --> 00:05:25,086
Well, it's good timing.  I'll be going, too--my relative's place, next Monday.

164
00:05:25,086 --> 00:05:26,030
 

165
00:05:26,030 --> 00:05:29,044
So maybe no one will come to exercises for a while.

166
00:05:29,044 --> 00:05:32,055
 

167
00:05:32,055 --> 00:05:34,052
Hello, Okajima residence.

168
00:05:34,052 --> 00:05:34,052
 

169
00:05:34,052 --> 00:05:37,000
Ah, Nanako `ne-san?  It's me, Taeko.

170
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 

171
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:41,054
I'm leaving today, and was wondering if Mitsuo `ni-san had anything for me to tell his family at the farm.

172
00:05:41,054 --> 00:05:41,056
 

173
00:05:41,056 --> 00:05:43,084
Hmm...doesn't seem like he had anything special to say...

174
00:05:43,084 --> 00:05:43,084
 

175
00:05:43,084 --> 00:05:50,001
...oh yeah, would you buy some cookies or something for Naoko-chan?  Say it's from Mitsuo Oji-chan and me, and I'll pay you back later.

176
00:05:50,001 --> 00:05:50,048
 

177
00:05:50,048 --> 00:05:53,042
That's fine...I'll say hello for you.  How's Mother?

178
00:05:53,042 --> 00:05:53,042
 

179
00:05:53,042 --> 00:05:55,006
She went out today.

180
00:05:55,006 --> 00:05:55,006
 

181
00:05:55,006 --> 00:05:59,064
She was angry, though--after all, you did turn down her Ohmiai [<arranged marriage (traditional)>] meeting, didn't you?

182
00:05:59,064 --> 00:05:59,064
 

183
00:05:59,064 --> 00:06:03,050
Considering that you're 27, you're not going to get any better choices for a husband.

184
00:06:03,050 --> 00:06:03,052
 

185
00:06:03,052 --> 00:06:06,018
That's all Mother ever talks about.

186
00:06:06,018 --> 00:06:06,020
 

187
00:06:06,020 --> 00:06:10,002
But you should think about it, you know.  You're not so young anymore.

188
00:06:10,002 --> 00:06:10,004
 

189
00:06:10,004 --> 00:06:11,062
Is that so?

190
00:06:11,062 --> 00:06:11,064
 

191
00:06:11,064 --> 00:06:15,048
Yes, it is--you can't be a cute little girl forever.

192
00:06:15,048 --> 00:06:15,056
 

193
00:06:15,056 --> 00:06:20,018
You can be so impulsive--you actually pitched in with the farming last year, didn't you?

194
00:06:20,018 --> 00:06:20,030
 

195
00:06:20,030 --> 00:06:23,074
Yeah, harvesting rice!  And this year, I'm going to pick benibana [<safflower>].

196
00:06:23,074 --> 00:06:23,076
 

197
00:06:23,076 --> 00:06:24,088
Benibana?

198
00:06:24,088 --> 00:06:24,090
 

199
00:06:24,090 --> 00:06:32,018
That's right!  Because of your husband's family in the country, I can have a hometown. I might as well make the most of it!

200
00:06:32,018 --> 00:06:34,015
 

201
00:06:34,015 --> 00:06:35,098
Oh, cut that out.

202
00:06:35,098 --> 00:06:35,098
 

203
00:06:35,098 --> 00:06:43,034
You don't get a vacation like this often, so instead of staying at such an old place, why not go to a nice rental cottage and have a "delicious life"?

204
00:06:43,034 --> 00:06:44,006
 

205
00:06:44,006 --> 00:06:46,020
You might be able to meet a nice guy.

206
00:06:46,020 --> 00:06:46,022
 

207
00:06:46,022 --> 00:06:50,076
Stop, stop!  You're trying to trick me again, like you did with the Pansy Bath at Ohnohya!

208
00:06:50,076 --> 00:06:50,076
 

209
00:06:50,076 --> 00:06:56,012
Ohnohya..?  Oh...ah, that time, huh?

210
00:06:56,012 --> 00:06:57,046
 

211
00:06:57,046 --> 00:07:03,024
You just talked about that a while ago, too.  What a burden your past must be if you're still holding a grudge like that!

212
00:07:03,024 --> 00:07:12,070
 

213
00:07:12,070 --> 00:07:17,002
At that time, my sisters wouldn't have been caught dead going to a place like Atami.

214
00:07:17,002 --> 00:07:19,004
 

215
00:07:19,004 --> 00:07:21,024
Hey Grandma.

216
00:07:21,024 --> 00:07:21,024
 

217
00:07:21,024 --> 00:07:21,098
Hmm...?

218
00:07:21,098 --> 00:07:22,040
 

219
00:07:22,040 --> 00:07:23,082
Done yet?

220
00:07:23,082 --> 00:07:25,012
 

221
00:07:25,012 --> 00:07:27,004
C'mon, let's go to the bath.

222
00:07:27,004 --> 00:07:27,055
 

223
00:07:27,055 --> 00:07:29,034
Didn't we just go?

224
00:07:29,034 --> 00:07:29,054
 

225
00:07:29,054 --> 00:07:31,084
But that was only to the Swan Bath.

226
00:07:31,084 --> 00:07:34,034
 

227
00:07:34,034 --> 00:07:39,010
I was incredibly bored. So starting with the Grimm Bath...

228
00:07:39,010 --> 00:07:39,010
 

229
00:07:39,010 --> 00:07:40,040
...and then to the Mermaid Bath...

230
00:07:40,040 --> 00:07:40,040
 

231
00:07:40,040 --> 00:07:41,073
...the Lemon Bath...

232
00:07:41,073 --> 00:07:41,073
 

233
00:07:41,073 --> 00:07:43,077
...and the Pansy Bath...

234
00:07:43,077 --> 00:07:43,086
 

235
00:07:43,086 --> 00:07:45,096
...I went from one to the next on my own.

236
00:07:45,096 --> 00:07:45,098
 

237
00:07:45,098 --> 00:07:47,084
It's enormous!

238
00:07:47,084 --> 00:07:48,026
 

239
00:07:48,026 --> 00:07:51,066
By the time I had reached the Roman Bath, I was starting to feel dizzy...

240
00:07:51,066 --> 00:07:53,067
 

241
00:07:53,067 --> 00:07:55,022
Wow...!

242
00:07:55,022 --> 00:08:05,060
 

243
00:08:05,060 --> 00:08:07,012
...And I finally passed out.

244
00:08:07,012 --> 00:08:08,008
 

245
00:08:08,008 --> 00:08:10,060
Thus my much-anticipated one-night trip came to an abrupt end,

246
00:08:10,060 --> 00:08:10,060
 

247
00:08:10,060 --> 00:08:14,013
and was followed by a long, long Summer vacation that was still waiting for me.

248
00:08:14,013 --> 00:08:14,017
 

249
00:08:14,017 --> 00:08:27,083
...Jumping jacks--open, close, open, close.  Next, arm and leg exercises.  1,2,3...

250
00:08:27,083 --> 00:08:28,096
 

251
00:08:28,096 --> 00:08:35,038
When I met with my sisters last time, I slipped and mentioned the disastrous bath trip, so we laughed,

252
00:08:35,038 --> 00:08:35,040
 

253
00:08:35,040 --> 00:08:42,014
``Oh yeah, and then there was that time...'', and the conversation turned to other memories of those days.

254
00:08:42,014 --> 00:08:45,036
 

255
00:08:45,036 --> 00:08:48,068
You've eaten this before?

256
00:08:48,068 --> 00:08:48,070
 

257
00:08:48,070 --> 00:08:50,020
Nope, my first time.

258
00:08:50,020 --> 00:08:50,020
 

259
00:08:50,020 --> 00:08:52,058
Remember, I'm the one who asked for it.

260
00:08:52,058 --> 00:08:52,060
 

261
00:08:52,060 --> 00:08:53,090
We know.

262
00:08:53,090 --> 00:08:53,092
 

263
00:08:53,092 --> 00:08:55,086
Where did you buy it, Dad?

264
00:08:55,086 --> 00:08:55,088
 

265
00:08:55,088 --> 00:08:57,088
The Senbiki shop in Ginza.

266
00:08:57,088 --> 00:08:57,088
 

267
00:08:57,088 --> 00:08:59,072
It was expensive, then?

268
00:08:59,072 --> 00:09:00,088
 

269
00:09:00,088 --> 00:09:02,038
So, how do we eat this?

270
00:09:02,038 --> 00:09:02,040
 

271
00:09:02,040 --> 00:09:03,092
We slice it into rings.

272
00:09:03,092 --> 00:09:03,094
 

273
00:09:03,094 --> 00:09:04,092
How?

274
00:09:04,092 --> 00:09:07,056
 

275
00:09:07,056 --> 00:09:08,050
...I don't know.

276
00:09:08,050 --> 00:09:10,008
 

277
00:09:10,008 --> 00:09:12,052
Father, didn't you ask the people at the shop?

278
00:09:12,052 --> 00:09:13,014
 

279
00:09:13,014 --> 00:09:13,082
Uh-uh.

280
00:09:13,082 --> 00:09:18,028
 

281
00:09:18,028 --> 00:09:20,022
Let's eat it next Sunday.

282
00:09:20,022 --> 00:09:20,044
 

283
00:09:20,044 --> 00:09:23,020
Huh---we're not going to eat it today?

284
00:09:23,020 --> 00:09:23,052
 

285
00:09:23,052 --> 00:09:25,038
But we don't know how to eat it, do we?

286
00:09:25,038 --> 00:09:28,024
 

287
00:09:28,024 --> 00:09:29,094
I'm gonna eat a banana.

288
00:09:29,094 --> 00:09:30,024
 

289
00:09:30,024 --> 00:09:31,064
Me too!

290
00:09:31,064 --> 00:09:35,044
 

291
00:09:35,044 --> 00:09:39,022
Warmer countries have rather unusual fruit, don't they?

292
00:09:39,022 --> 00:09:42,071
 

293
00:09:42,071 --> 00:09:43,065
I'm home!

294
00:09:43,065 --> 00:09:44,054
 

295
00:09:44,054 --> 00:09:46,058
I found out how to serve pineapple.

296
00:09:46,058 --> 00:09:46,060
 

297
00:09:46,060 --> 00:09:47,096
What, really?

298
00:09:47,096 --> 00:09:52,092
 

299
00:09:52,092 --> 00:09:53,090
I..I'll get that.

300
00:09:53,090 --> 00:09:54,082
 

301
00:09:54,082 --> 00:09:55,094
Carefully, now.

302
00:09:55,094 --> 00:09:56,028
 

303
00:09:56,028 --> 00:09:57,090
Wouldn't a fish knife be better?

304
00:09:57,090 --> 00:10:11,064
 

305
00:10:11,064 --> 00:10:13,022
Nice smell, nice smell!

306
00:10:13,022 --> 00:10:22,088
 

307
00:10:22,088 --> 00:10:24,058
Nice fragrance, nice fragrance!

308
00:10:24,058 --> 00:10:27,042
 

309
00:10:27,042 --> 00:10:28,050
Oh, I see.

310
00:10:28,050 --> 00:10:30,030
 

311
00:10:30,030 --> 00:10:31,056
Hey--plates, plates!

312
00:10:31,056 --> 00:10:31,058
 

313
00:10:31,058 --> 00:10:33,022
..Oh, right!

314
00:10:33,022 --> 00:10:35,060
 

315
00:10:35,060 --> 00:10:36,022
Itadakimasu [We shall try it now].

316
00:10:36,022 --> 00:10:36,024
 

317
00:10:36,024 --> 00:10:37,064
Itadakimasu [Let's try it].

318
00:10:37,064 --> 00:10:58,066
 

319
00:10:58,066 --> 00:10:59,082
It's tough.

320
00:10:59,082 --> 00:11:04,062
 

321
00:11:04,062 --> 00:11:06,040
Not such a big deal.

322
00:11:06,040 --> 00:11:06,052
 

323
00:11:06,052 --> 00:11:08,018
Not very sweet at all.

324
00:11:08,018 --> 00:11:08,020
 

325
00:11:08,020 --> 00:11:10,030
It's completely different from when it's canned.

326
00:11:10,030 --> 00:11:10,041
 

327
00:11:10,041 --> 00:11:13,058
If you live a long time, you get to have many experiences.

328
00:11:13,058 --> 00:11:19,048
 

329
00:11:19,048 --> 00:11:20,048
Taeko can have mine.

330
00:11:20,048 --> 00:11:20,050
 

331
00:11:20,050 --> 00:11:21,048
Mine too.

332
00:11:21,048 --> 00:11:51,046
 

333
00:11:51,046 --> 00:11:53,010
...Delicious...

334
00:11:53,010 --> 00:11:58,072
 

335
00:11:58,072 --> 00:12:00,088
You don't have to force yourself to eat it.

336
00:12:00,088 --> 00:12:01,002
 

337
00:12:01,002 --> 00:12:02,026
You'll get a stomachache.

338
00:12:02,026 --> 00:12:11,048
 

339
00:12:11,048 --> 00:12:14,072
Oh well, that was boring.

340
00:12:14,072 --> 00:12:17,062
 

341
00:12:17,062 --> 00:12:19,094
Bananas are far more tasty, aren't they?

342
00:12:19,094 --> 00:12:19,096
 

343
00:12:19,096 --> 00:12:21,028
True, true.

344
00:12:21,028 --> 00:12:21,030
 

345
00:12:21,030 --> 00:12:24,032
As I expected, the banana is the king of fruit, I guess.

346
00:12:24,032 --> 00:12:24,052
 

347
00:12:24,052 --> 00:12:26,010
I'm gonna have a banana.

348
00:12:26,010 --> 00:12:50,044
 

349
00:12:50,044 --> 00:12:53,060
As I thought, the king of fruit is...

350
00:12:53,060 --> 00:12:54,010
 

351
00:12:54,010 --> 00:12:55,088
the king of fruit is...

352
00:12:55,088 --> 00:12:56,052
 

353
00:12:56,052 --> 00:12:58,000
...the banana!

354
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:03,076
 

355
00:13:03,076 --> 00:13:08,086
The year I passed out at the Roman Bath and ate pineapple for the first time,

356
00:13:08,086 --> 00:13:08,088
 

357
00:13:08,088 --> 00:13:13,042
was the same year that the "group sound" became a fad, starting with the Beatles' visit to Japan.

358
00:13:13,042 --> 00:13:13,044
 

359
00:13:13,044 --> 00:13:15,092
Soon after that, the electric guitar boom would come.

360
00:13:15,092 --> 00:13:19,078
 

361
00:13:19,078 --> 00:13:24,050
My sister Nanako 'ne-san was a freshman at an art college, and was always the first to try out all the new fads.

362
00:13:24,050 --> 00:13:25,024
 

363
00:13:25,024 --> 00:13:28,030
Yeah, ``Michelle,'' isn't it?   Another cool Beatles song, huh?

364
00:13:28,030 --> 00:13:28,030
 

365
00:13:28,030 --> 00:13:35,006
She tried the mini-skirt when it first came out, and like everyone else, she hid her behind with a bag whenever going upstairs.

366
00:13:35,006 --> 00:13:38,030
 

367
00:13:38,030 --> 00:13:43,090
My other sister, Yaeko 'ne-san, the smart eleventh grader, was completely in love with someone in the Takarazuka theater [all-female theater].

368
00:13:43,090 --> 00:13:44,002
 

369
00:13:44,002 --> 00:13:45,030
Yaeko 'ne-chan...

370
00:13:45,030 --> 00:13:46,002
 

371
00:13:46,002 --> 00:13:48,026
D....didn't I tell you to always knock first??!!

372
00:13:48,026 --> 00:13:52,064
 

373
00:13:52,064 --> 00:13:57,092
The memories that my sisters mainly talked about were the stars and fashions that they were into.

374
00:13:57,092 --> 00:13:58,034
 

375
00:13:58,034 --> 00:14:07,028
1966 was a memorable teenage year for my sisters.  But back then, I was only in the 5th grade.

376
00:14:07,028 --> 00:14:08,024
 

377
00:14:08,024 --> 00:14:12,012
I became a fan of Julie of The Tigers...but they didn't debut until later.

378
00:14:12,012 --> 00:14:12,032
 

379
00:14:12,032 --> 00:14:17,046
There was no way for me to have big dreams in the days when I was just simply going back and forth between school and home.

380
00:14:17,046 --> 00:14:17,046
 

381
00:14:17,046 --> 00:14:18,096
...and it's been on the wall for a long time.

382
00:14:18,096 --> 00:14:18,096
 

383
00:14:18,096 --> 00:14:21,054
That's nice.

384
00:14:21,054 --> 00:14:21,056
 

385
00:14:21,056 --> 00:14:30,010
And I was told to keep the essay I wrote on the book, because they might send it to a contest. If that happens, I'll be very happy...

386
00:14:30,010 --> 00:14:30,012
 

387
00:14:30,012 --> 00:14:31,082
You didn't eat your school lunch again.

388
00:14:31,082 --> 00:14:32,052
 

389
00:14:32,052 --> 00:14:33,004
...huh?

390
00:14:33,004 --> 00:14:33,006
 

391
00:14:33,006 --> 00:14:35,038
Why do you put it between bread?

392
00:14:35,038 --> 00:14:35,038
 

393
00:14:35,038 --> 00:14:37,046
Because I hate namasu<daikon radish and carrots marinated in vinegar>.

394
00:14:37,046 --> 00:14:37,048
 

395
00:14:37,048 --> 00:14:40,068
Well, if you do this, we can't use the bread or the namasu.

396
00:14:40,068 --> 00:14:41,076
 

397
00:14:41,076 --> 00:14:43,078
How wasteful.

398
00:14:43,078 --> 00:14:44,032
 

399
00:14:44,032 --> 00:14:50,078
The kid who can eat all of her food is more respected than the one who can write an essay.

400
00:14:50,078 --> 00:15:06,094
 

401
00:15:06,094 --> 00:15:10,054
Wow, how can you drink that tasteless stuff?

402
00:15:10,054 --> 00:15:12,003
 

403
00:15:12,003 --> 00:15:15,091
The milk's all right.  It's the daikon radish and onion I can't stand.

404
00:15:15,091 --> 00:15:16,011
 

405
00:15:16,011 --> 00:15:19,090
Since I'm leaving carrots today, I have to drink the milk.

406
00:15:19,090 --> 00:15:20,052
 

407
00:15:20,052 --> 00:15:24,099
I wonder who decided you could only leave one thing?

408
00:15:24,099 --> 00:15:25,025
 

409
00:15:25,025 --> 00:15:26,006
Want me to drink it?

410
00:15:26,006 --> 00:15:26,034
 

411
00:15:26,034 --> 00:15:27,090
W..would you?

412
00:15:27,090 --> 00:15:27,092
 

413
00:15:27,092 --> 00:15:31,008
And next time, you could eat my daikon or onion in return?

414
00:15:31,008 --> 00:15:31,056
 

415
00:15:31,056 --> 00:15:33,020
Uh-huh, uh-huh, uh-huh.

416
00:15:33,020 --> 00:15:39,080
 

417
00:15:39,080 --> 00:15:40,042
``Thank you!''

418
00:15:40,042 --> 00:15:43,028
 

419
00:15:43,028 --> 00:15:44,042
Aah, carrots!?

420
00:15:44,042 --> 00:15:44,042
 

421
00:15:44,042 --> 00:15:45,066
You can leave one thing, you know...

422
00:15:45,066 --> 00:15:55,004
 

423
00:15:55,004 --> 00:15:56,088
I was right, the second bowl is worse...

424
00:15:56,088 --> 00:15:57,084
 

425
00:15:57,084 --> 00:16:03,038
There are people who keep running if they are told to start over again by the hall monitors.

426
00:16:03,038 --> 00:16:03,040
 

427
00:16:03,040 --> 00:16:05,072
I think to keep running is really bad.

428
00:16:05,072 --> 00:16:06,002
 

429
00:16:06,002 --> 00:16:09,036
``Start over again?''  Spare me.

430
00:16:09,036 --> 00:16:09,058
 

431
00:16:09,058 --> 00:16:11,002
You can't run in the halls.

432
00:16:11,002 --> 00:16:11,040
 

433
00:16:11,040 --> 00:16:12,062
That's right, that's right.

434
00:16:12,062 --> 00:16:12,076
 

435
00:16:12,076 --> 00:16:14,063
It's dangerous--you might hurt somebody.

436
00:16:14,063 --> 00:16:14,076
 

437
00:16:14,076 --> 00:16:18,070
No way--if I hit a girl like you, Toko, I would be the one hurt.

438
00:16:18,070 --> 00:16:18,070
 

439
00:16:18,070 --> 00:16:20,004
Oh, PLEASE...

440
00:16:20,004 --> 00:16:20,004
 

441
00:16:20,004 --> 00:16:21,010
I'm hit!

442
00:16:21,010 --> 00:16:22,020
 

443
00:16:22,020 --> 00:16:24,052
Once you ran, what can you do about it?

444
00:16:24,052 --> 00:16:25,001
 

445
00:16:25,001 --> 00:16:25,081
Here, here.

446
00:16:25,081 --> 00:16:25,081
 

447
00:16:25,081 --> 00:16:26,069
Be quiet.

448
00:16:26,069 --> 00:16:26,069
 

449
00:16:26,069 --> 00:16:28,041
Why not abolish the system of starting over?

450
00:16:28,041 --> 00:16:28,041
 

451
00:16:28,041 --> 00:16:29,094
You can't, it's part of the rules.

452
00:16:29,094 --> 00:16:30,045
 

453
00:16:30,045 --> 00:16:32,082
If you have an opinion, please raise your hand.

454
00:16:32,082 --> 00:16:32,084
 

455
00:16:32,084 --> 00:16:33,076
I do.

456
00:16:33,076 --> 00:16:33,076
 

457
00:16:33,076 --> 00:16:35,014
Tani-san.

458
00:16:35,014 --> 00:16:36,056
 

459
00:16:36,056 --> 00:16:43,004
I think the hall monitor should run after the runner, catch them, and make them go back and start over.

460
00:16:43,004 --> 00:16:43,032
 

461
00:16:43,032 --> 00:16:44,066
I do!

462
00:16:44,066 --> 00:16:44,068
 

463
00:16:44,068 --> 00:16:45,070
Suzuki-san.

464
00:16:45,070 --> 00:16:47,008
 

465
00:16:47,008 --> 00:16:50,084
And then the hall monitor has to go back and start over, too.

466
00:16:50,084 --> 00:16:51,006
 

467
00:16:51,006 --> 00:16:52,046
Right, right!

468
00:16:52,046 --> 00:16:52,074
 

469
00:16:52,074 --> 00:16:54,018
That's more like it!

470
00:16:54,018 --> 00:16:54,048
 

471
00:16:54,048 --> 00:16:55,054
That's right.

472
00:16:55,054 --> 00:16:55,056
 

473
00:16:55,056 --> 00:16:57,020
Yes, Tani Tsuneko-san.

474
00:16:57,020 --> 00:16:57,022
 

475
00:16:57,022 --> 00:17:01,044
I don't think that the hall monitors need to start over because...

476
00:17:01,044 --> 00:17:01,046
 

477
00:17:01,046 --> 00:17:08,034
...their job is just like a police patrol car catching a speeder.

478
00:17:08,034 --> 00:17:14,090
 

479
00:17:14,090 --> 00:17:16,070
Any opposing arguments?

480
00:17:16,070 --> 00:17:19,004
 

481
00:17:19,004 --> 00:17:20,044
Like a patrol car...?

482
00:17:20,044 --> 00:17:20,082
 

483
00:17:20,082 --> 00:17:22,002
...Then running is no good.

484
00:17:22,002 --> 00:17:23,002
 

485
00:17:23,002 --> 00:17:27,086
The decision rests on allowing the hall monitor to run.

486
00:17:27,086 --> 00:17:30,044
 

487
00:17:30,044 --> 00:17:32,006
Anything else to discuss?

488
00:17:32,006 --> 00:17:32,036
 

489
00:17:32,036 --> 00:17:33,024
Yes.

490
00:17:33,024 --> 00:17:33,026
 

491
00:17:33,026 --> 00:17:34,044
Tani-san.

492
00:17:34,044 --> 00:17:35,024
 

493
00:17:35,024 --> 00:17:36,020
Her again?!

494
00:17:36,020 --> 00:17:36,022
 

495
00:17:36,022 --> 00:17:37,000
The show-off!

496
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:37,002
 

497
00:17:37,002 --> 00:17:38,028
Quit chattering.

498
00:17:38,028 --> 00:17:38,056
 

499
00:17:38,056 --> 00:17:45,068
Lately I've been seeing people leaving food at lunch.  I just read a magazine article about the war in Vietnam.

500
00:17:45,068 --> 00:17:46,020
 

501
00:17:46,020 --> 00:17:51,068
In foreign countries like those there are many poor people.  We are happily more fortunate.

502
00:17:51,068 --> 00:17:51,070
 

503
00:17:51,070 --> 00:17:53,010
Yeah,``we're happy.''

504
00:17:53,010 --> 00:17:56,078
 

505
00:17:56,078 --> 00:17:59,072
We must be thankful for the food we have.

506
00:17:59,072 --> 00:18:00,018
 

507
00:18:00,018 --> 00:18:06,095
Right now we may leave one thing per meal, but I feel that is too lenient.

508
00:18:06,095 --> 00:18:09,075
 

509
00:18:09,075 --> 00:18:12,016
Geez, Tsuneko...aren't you the goody two-shoes?

510
00:18:12,016 --> 00:18:12,027
 

511
00:18:12,027 --> 00:18:12,088
Bleah!

512
00:18:12,088 --> 00:18:12,090
 

513
00:18:12,090 --> 00:18:15,000
Why can't we leave even one thing?

514
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:15,000
 

515
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,006
And then everyone could leave the milk.

516
00:18:17,006 --> 00:18:17,008
 

517
00:18:17,008 --> 00:18:19,038
Why not ask somebody to eat what you don't like?

518
00:18:19,038 --> 00:18:19,040
 

519
00:18:19,040 --> 00:18:20,060
That's obvious.

520
00:18:20,060 --> 00:18:20,062
 

521
00:18:20,062 --> 00:18:22,080
Some people leave extra by hiding it between their bread.

522
00:18:22,080 --> 00:18:22,080
 

523
00:18:22,080 --> 00:18:24,042
Ohh, cheaters!

524
00:18:24,042 --> 00:18:25,003
 

525
00:18:25,003 --> 00:18:26,044
School lunch stinks.

526
00:18:26,044 --> 00:18:26,046
 

527
00:18:26,046 --> 00:18:27,044
If you have an opinion..

528
00:18:27,044 --> 00:18:27,049
 

529
00:18:27,049 --> 00:18:30,050
If you have an opinion, raise your hand, please!

530
00:18:30,050 --> 00:18:30,054
 

531
00:18:30,054 --> 00:18:32,062
``Oh...you got me!''

532
00:18:32,062 --> 00:18:36,006
 

533
00:18:36,006 --> 00:18:47,052
After I said goodbye to my sisters and went to bed, one by one, my memories of fifth grade came back.

534
00:18:47,052 --> 00:18:51,030
 

535
00:18:51,030 --> 00:18:53,042
Memories about our dog, Gon...

536
00:18:53,042 --> 00:18:53,042
 

537
00:18:53,042 --> 00:18:56,016
...about sports day...

538
00:18:56,016 --> 00:18:56,018
 

539
00:18:56,018 --> 00:18:59,060
...about the scary feeling we got from reading Kazuo Umezu's comics...

540
00:18:59,060 --> 00:18:59,062
 

541
00:18:59,062 --> 00:19:03,008
...and even about yearning for an electric pencil sharpener.

542
00:19:03,008 --> 00:19:05,020
 

543
00:19:05,020 --> 00:19:16,018
Even such trivial things came back vividly, occupying my mind as if I were watching a movie, and overwhelmed the real me.

544
00:19:16,018 --> 00:19:22,000
 

545
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:24,004
Is there an ``Okajima-san'' here?

546
00:19:24,004 --> 00:19:25,038
 

547
00:19:25,038 --> 00:19:26,012
There's the one.

548
00:19:26,012 --> 00:19:38,020
 

549
00:19:38,020 --> 00:19:41,052
Hirota-kun says that ``I like Okajima-san of room 5.''

550
00:19:41,052 --> 00:19:46,056
 

551
00:19:46,056 --> 00:19:47,034
...Shall we go?

552
00:19:47,034 --> 00:19:50,054
 

553
00:19:50,054 --> 00:19:52,094
I'm gonna tell Hiro that you know, now!

554
00:19:52,094 --> 00:19:53,054
 

555
00:19:53,054 --> 00:19:54,012
Hurry up!

556
00:19:54,012 --> 00:19:55,045
 

557
00:19:55,045 --> 00:19:56,061
You see?

558
00:19:56,061 --> 00:20:03,012
 

559
00:20:03,012 --> 00:20:04,052
Where, where?

560
00:20:04,052 --> 00:20:04,054
 

561
00:20:04,054 --> 00:20:05,050
Over there.

562
00:20:05,050 --> 00:20:07,048
 

563
00:20:07,048 --> 00:20:08,089
Oh, she's right!

564
00:20:08,089 --> 00:20:09,026
 

565
00:20:09,026 --> 00:20:09,080
See?

566
00:20:09,080 --> 00:20:12,018
 

567
00:20:12,018 --> 00:20:13,070
What kind of guy is Hirota-kun?

568
00:20:13,070 --> 00:20:13,072
 

569
00:20:13,072 --> 00:20:14,084
I don't know.

570
00:20:14,084 --> 00:20:14,086
 

571
00:20:14,086 --> 00:20:15,064
Me neither.

572
00:20:15,064 --> 00:20:15,066
 

573
00:20:15,066 --> 00:20:18,008
Taeko-chan, are you sure you don't know him?

574
00:20:18,008 --> 00:20:18,008
 

575
00:20:18,008 --> 00:20:20,076
I..I..I don't know him.  Not at all.

576
00:20:20,076 --> 00:20:26,008
 

577
00:20:26,008 --> 00:20:28,006
Which one here is named Hirota-kun?

578
00:20:28,006 --> 00:20:28,038
 

579
00:20:28,038 --> 00:20:29,050
Oh, it's some room 5 kids.

580
00:20:29,050 --> 00:20:29,068
 

581
00:20:29,068 --> 00:20:31,000
Hiro, you're being called.

582
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:34,014
 

583
00:20:34,014 --> 00:20:35,070
Yes, that's me!

584
00:20:35,070 --> 00:20:36,076
 

585
00:20:36,076 --> 00:20:39,084
D...don't write strange things at ``Naughty Alley''...

586
00:20:39,084 --> 00:20:39,090
 

587
00:20:39,090 --> 00:20:40,052
Huh?

588
00:20:40,052 --> 00:20:40,054
 

589
00:20:40,054 --> 00:20:42,006
...Okajima-san said to tell you.

590
00:20:42,006 --> 00:20:42,032
 

591
00:20:42,032 --> 00:20:44,058
I...I didn't write anything.

592
00:20:44,058 --> 00:20:44,060
 

593
00:20:44,060 --> 00:20:48,022
Ah, but Hiro, didn't you say you liked ``Okajima-san from room 5?''

594
00:20:48,022 --> 00:20:48,024
 

595
00:20:48,024 --> 00:20:49,044
He did, he did!

596
00:20:49,044 --> 00:20:49,072
 

597
00:20:49,072 --> 00:20:51,028
So we wrote it for you.

598
00:20:51,028 --> 00:20:51,028
 

599
00:20:51,028 --> 00:20:52,040
Whaa...?!

600
00:20:52,040 --> 00:20:53,002
 

601
00:20:53,002 --> 00:20:55,082
``I love you, but...''

