914
00:34:08,068 --> 00:34:08,070
 

915
00:34:08,070 --> 00:34:12,068
So that's why sometimes I skip P.E. class.

916
00:34:12,068 --> 00:34:13,006
 

917
00:34:13,006 --> 00:34:15,020
You skip P.E. when you have your period?

918
00:34:15,020 --> 00:34:15,052
 

919
00:34:15,052 --> 00:34:18,030
Right, my mother told me I should.

920
00:34:18,030 --> 00:34:20,010
 

921
00:34:20,010 --> 00:34:23,092
Nakayama-kun said that it must be a big bother for girls after I told him.

922
00:34:23,092 --> 00:34:24,092
 

923
00:34:24,092 --> 00:34:26,066
You told him about skipping P.E. class?!

924
00:34:26,066 --> 00:34:27,006
 

925
00:34:27,006 --> 00:34:32,028
Uh-huh, though I told him to keep his promise and not tell any other boys.

926
00:34:32,028 --> 00:34:32,030
 

927
00:34:32,030 --> 00:34:33,094
If you told him that...

928
00:34:33,094 --> 00:34:34,018
 

929
00:34:34,018 --> 00:34:37,028
When any girl skips P.E. class, everyone will think she's having her period, won't they?!

930
00:34:37,028 --> 00:34:37,030
 

931
00:34:37,030 --> 00:34:38,064
Huh, you think so?

932
00:34:38,064 --> 00:34:38,064
 

933
00:34:38,064 --> 00:34:39,078
Darn right!

934
00:34:39,078 --> 00:34:40,056
 

935
00:34:40,056 --> 00:34:43,036
...really?  I'll have to tell the guys.  Hey...!

936
00:34:43,036 --> 00:34:44,078
 

937
00:34:44,078 --> 00:34:46,056
Please excuse Taeko from P.E. class because of the flu.

938
00:34:46,056 --> 00:34:52,084
 

939
00:34:52,084 --> 00:34:54,062
I'm not going to skip P.E.

940
00:34:54,062 --> 00:34:54,064
 

941
00:34:54,064 --> 00:34:58,018
Forget it--that summer flu will only get much worse if you don't skip it.

942
00:34:58,018 --> 00:34:58,018
 

943
00:34:58,018 --> 00:34:59,088
Well, then I'm staying home.

944
00:34:59,088 --> 00:34:59,088
 

945
00:34:59,088 --> 00:35:02,028
You don't have a fever, so you're going.

946
00:35:02,028 --> 00:35:02,030
 

947
00:35:02,030 --> 00:35:03,088
Then I'll go to P.E., too.

948
00:35:03,088 --> 00:35:03,088
 

949
00:35:03,088 --> 00:35:05,048
Fine, go ahead.

950
00:35:05,048 --> 00:35:06,006
 

951
00:35:06,006 --> 00:35:08,048
But then if you get worse, it's on your head.

952
00:35:08,048 --> 00:35:12,032
 

953
00:35:12,032 --> 00:35:13,042
I'm going now.

954
00:35:13,042 --> 00:35:14,086
 

955
00:35:14,086 --> 00:35:17,092
I wonder when she started liking P.E. so much...

956
00:35:17,092 --> 00:35:24,037
 

957
00:35:24,037 --> 00:35:26,046
Taeko-chan, your face is real red.

958
00:35:26,046 --> 00:35:26,076
 

959
00:35:26,076 --> 00:35:28,030
Oh, it really is.

960
00:35:28,030 --> 00:35:28,044
 

961
00:35:28,044 --> 00:35:29,068
What's the matter?

962
00:35:29,068 --> 00:35:29,070
 

963
00:35:29,070 --> 00:35:31,022
Its a cold.

964
00:35:31,022 --> 00:35:31,024
 

965
00:35:31,024 --> 00:35:32,060
Do you have a fever?

966
00:35:32,060 --> 00:35:32,062
 

967
00:35:32,062 --> 00:35:33,092
You ought to skip P.E.

968
00:35:33,092 --> 00:35:33,094
 

969
00:35:33,094 --> 00:35:35,018
She's right.

970
00:35:35,018 --> 00:35:35,064
 

971
00:35:35,064 --> 00:35:36,078
I'll go tell the teacher.

972
00:35:36,078 --> 00:35:37,048
 

973
00:35:37,048 --> 00:35:38,032
That's okay!

974
00:35:38,032 --> 00:35:38,066
 

975
00:35:38,066 --> 00:35:39,074
But...

976
00:35:39,074 --> 00:35:40,052
 

977
00:35:40,052 --> 00:35:42,082
I have a note to excuse me from P.E.

978
00:35:42,082 --> 00:35:43,008
 

979
00:35:43,008 --> 00:35:45,080
What, well, that's okay then.

980
00:35:45,080 --> 00:35:46,084
 

981
00:35:46,084 --> 00:35:47,084
Right?

982
00:35:47,084 --> 00:35:48,046
 

983
00:35:48,046 --> 00:35:49,054
Gangway!

984
00:35:49,054 --> 00:35:57,006
 

985
00:35:57,006 --> 00:36:00,038
I'm also skipping it today, so we're together.

986
00:36:00,038 --> 00:36:07,096
 

987
00:36:07,096 --> 00:36:10,030
That looks nice...

988
00:36:10,030 --> 00:36:10,032
 

989
00:36:10,032 --> 00:36:12,068
I wish I could be playing dodge-ball.

990
00:36:12,068 --> 00:36:16,080
 

991
00:36:16,080 --> 00:36:22,040
Rie-chan, do you...that is, are you...having your period?

992
00:36:22,040 --> 00:36:23,007
 

993
00:36:23,007 --> 00:36:24,008
Mmm-hmmm.

994
00:36:24,008 --> 00:36:26,004
 

995
00:36:26,004 --> 00:36:28,040
I'm not, I've got a cold.

996
00:36:28,040 --> 00:36:28,040
 

997
00:36:28,040 --> 00:36:31,026
I know that, Taeko-chan, you're just sick.

998
00:36:31,026 --> 00:36:31,028
 

999
00:36:31,028 --> 00:36:34,016
Right, just sick, that's what I am.

1000
00:36:34,016 --> 00:36:34,016
 

1001
00:36:34,016 --> 00:36:36,088
A period isn't being sick, of course.

1002
00:36:36,088 --> 00:36:42,078
 

1003
00:36:42,078 --> 00:36:45,082
I'm sure I could play dodge-ball.

1004
00:36:45,082 --> 00:36:49,014
 

1005
00:36:49,014 --> 00:36:50,020
Oh, period contagion!

1006
00:36:50,020 --> 00:36:50,032
 

1007
00:36:50,032 --> 00:36:51,024
Huh?

1008
00:36:51,024 --> 00:36:52,030
 

1009
00:36:52,030 --> 00:36:53,091
Back off, back off!

1010
00:36:53,091 --> 00:36:54,040
 

1011
00:36:54,040 --> 00:36:57,024
That was close--any further and we could have been contaminated!

1012
00:36:57,024 --> 00:36:57,062
 

1013
00:36:57,062 --> 00:36:59,028
(``Contaminated?!'')

1014
00:36:59,028 --> 00:37:01,002
 

1015
00:37:01,002 --> 00:37:02,044
Hey, over here!

1016
00:37:02,044 --> 00:37:04,038
 

1017
00:37:04,038 --> 00:37:06,026
Periods are contagious?

1018
00:37:06,026 --> 00:37:10,010
 

1019
00:37:10,010 --> 00:37:11,066
How stupid!

1020
00:37:11,066 --> 00:37:13,046
 

1021
00:37:13,046 --> 00:37:15,012
It...It's not funny!

1022
00:37:15,012 --> 00:37:18,096
 

1023
00:37:18,096 --> 00:37:20,046
Taeko-chan [Taeko]...?

1024
00:37:20,046 --> 00:37:27,098
 

1025
00:37:27,098 --> 00:37:29,032
Hey, a pair with periods!

1026
00:37:29,032 --> 00:37:29,034
 

1027
00:37:29,034 --> 00:37:30,056
It's not true!

1028
00:37:30,056 --> 00:37:31,070
 

1029
00:37:31,070 --> 00:37:32,096
What a pervert, huh?

1030
00:37:32,096 --> 00:37:41,060
 

1031
00:37:41,060 --> 00:37:43,086
Rie-chan, how can you stand this?

1032
00:37:43,086 --> 00:37:43,088
 

1033
00:37:43,088 --> 00:37:48,054
But it isn't really a bad thing, or so my mom tells me.

1034
00:37:48,054 --> 00:37:49,086
 

1035
00:37:49,086 --> 00:37:51,076
Well, I suppose so, but...

1036
00:37:51,076 --> 00:37:56,066
 

1037
00:37:56,066 --> 00:37:59,090
A larva has to become a pupa in order to become a butterfly.

1038
00:37:59,090 --> 00:38:02,034
 

1039
00:38:02,034 --> 00:38:05,024
I didn't want to become a pupa....

1040
00:38:05,024 --> 00:38:16,072
 

1041
00:38:16,072 --> 00:38:23,000
I wonder, maybe the reason I am remembering those days is because my period of becoming a pupa has come once again.

1042
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:27,024
 

1043
00:38:27,024 --> 00:38:32,020
I know something is different now compared to several years ago when I got my job.  I am changing again.

1044
00:38:32,020 --> 00:38:33,002
 

1045
00:38:33,002 --> 00:38:39,010
In work and play, we were always more lively than the boys.

1046
00:38:39,010 --> 00:38:40,020
 

1047
00:38:40,020 --> 00:38:42,048
We thought we had already flown away from home...

1048
00:38:42,048 --> 00:38:44,080
 

1049
00:38:44,080 --> 00:38:51,002
...but now I look back and think maybe we were just too busy flapping our wings and forgot who we were.

1050
00:38:51,002 --> 00:38:56,042
 

1051
00:38:56,042 --> 00:39:05,031
I wonder if the reason my fifth grade self is following me is that she is trying to tell me to look back and figure out who I am.

1052
00:39:05,031 --> 00:39:11,076
 

1053
00:39:11,076 --> 00:39:16,086
Whatever the case, I decided to take a short nap until I arrived in Yamagata.

1054
00:39:16,086 --> 00:40:04,006
 

1055
00:40:04,006 --> 00:40:05,013
Watch out.

1056
00:40:05,013 --> 00:40:15,006
 

1057
00:40:15,006 --> 00:40:17,058
'Scuse me--has the ``Akebono #3'' train already left?

1058
00:40:17,058 --> 00:40:17,070
 

1059
00:40:17,070 --> 00:40:19,060
You missed boarding it?

1060
00:40:19,060 --> 00:40:19,062
 

1061
00:40:19,062 --> 00:40:21,034
Er...no...

1062
00:40:21,034 --> 00:40:24,008
 

1063
00:40:24,008 --> 00:40:25,058
Oh!

1064
00:40:25,058 --> 00:40:27,066
 

1065
00:40:27,066 --> 00:40:30,024
You're...Taeko Okajima-san, right?

1066
00:40:30,024 --> 00:40:30,062
 

1067
00:40:30,062 --> 00:40:32,056
Well...yes...

1068
00:40:32,056 --> 00:40:32,080
 

1069
00:40:32,080 --> 00:40:35,068
Whew, that's good! The car's this way.

1070
00:40:35,068 --> 00:40:35,096
 

1071
00:40:35,096 --> 00:40:38,062
Um, er, excuse me, but just who ARE you?

1072
00:40:38,062 --> 00:40:39,088
 

1073
00:40:39,088 --> 00:40:41,028
Oh, don'tcha remember?

1074
00:40:41,028 --> 00:40:42,008
 

1075
00:40:42,008 --> 00:40:44,098
Well, can't say I blame you, there's small chance you would.

1076
00:40:44,098 --> 00:40:45,000
 

1077
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:48,092
I'm Toshio.  Um...Kazuo's second cousin.

1078
00:40:48,092 --> 00:40:50,075
 

1079
00:40:50,075 --> 00:40:54,054
Oh...ah, really...?

1080
00:40:54,054 --> 00:40:58,076
 

1081
00:40:58,076 --> 00:41:00,070
Oh dear.

1082
00:41:00,070 --> 00:41:02,054
 

1083
00:41:02,054 --> 00:41:03,076
What's so funny?

1084
00:41:03,076 --> 00:41:05,082
 

1085
00:41:05,082 --> 00:41:11,032
Oh, um, nothing.  I'm sorry, it's just I thought you were trying to steal my bag.

1086
00:41:11,032 --> 00:41:12,062
 

1087
00:41:12,062 --> 00:41:18,016
Huh, that's cruel--remember, I certainly made it clear I knew your name, didn't I?

1088
00:41:18,016 --> 00:41:18,018
 

1089
00:41:18,018 --> 00:41:26,062
I spoke too soon.  Thanks for coming out of your way to pick me up.  I'm sorry about this.

1090
00:41:26,062 --> 00:41:26,080
 

1091
00:41:26,080 --> 00:41:28,014
No trouble.

1092
00:41:28,014 --> 00:41:31,000
 

1093
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:32,036
What happened to Kazuo 'ni-san?

1094
00:41:32,036 --> 00:41:32,038
 

1095
00:41:32,038 --> 00:41:37,042
He suddenly called last night and asked me to pick you up instead.

1096
00:41:37,042 --> 00:41:38,046
 

1097
00:41:38,046 --> 00:41:39,084
It's been raining?

1098
00:41:39,084 --> 00:41:39,084
 

1099
00:41:39,084 --> 00:41:42,028
Yep, but it's stopped for today.

1100
00:41:42,028 --> 00:41:43,098
 

1101
00:41:43,098 --> 00:41:50,088
I should've borrowed my pa's car...but, well, I happen to like this one.

1102
00:41:50,088 --> 00:41:54,060
 

1103
00:41:54,060 --> 00:41:56,028
It's a little cramped, but hop in.

1104
00:41:56,028 --> 00:42:10,007
 

1105
00:42:10,007 --> 00:42:13,046
Oh, mind if I keep it on?

1106
00:42:13,046 --> 00:42:13,048
 

1107
00:42:13,048 --> 00:42:14,088
Um, sure.

1108
00:42:14,088 --> 00:42:45,050
 

1109
00:42:45,050 --> 00:42:47,046
What unusual music...

1110
00:42:47,046 --> 00:42:47,074
 

1111
00:42:47,074 --> 00:42:51,006
Its a group of five Hungarians called "Muzsikas".

1112
00:42:51,006 --> 00:42:51,006
 

1113
00:42:51,006 --> 00:42:53,032
Oh, Hungarian?

1114
00:42:53,032 --> 00:42:53,034
 

1115
00:42:53,034 --> 00:42:54,038
Yep.

1116
00:42:54,038 --> 00:42:54,064
 

1117
00:42:54,064 --> 00:42:55,098
Do you know much about it?

1118
00:42:55,098 --> 00:42:56,056
 

1119
00:42:56,056 --> 00:43:00,040
A little.  It's music for peasants.  I like it 'cause I'm one, too.

1120
00:43:00,040 --> 00:43:00,092
 

1121
00:43:00,092 --> 00:43:02,068
Wow, that's cool.

1122
00:43:02,068 --> 00:43:03,030
 

1123
00:43:03,030 --> 00:43:04,048
Isn't it?

1124
00:43:04,048 --> 00:43:28,000
 

1125
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:32,024
You recall the time,  when we all had a sake party at the main farmhouse after the rice harvest, that one time...?

1126
00:43:32,024 --> 00:43:32,026
 

1127
00:43:32,026 --> 00:43:33,072
Umm, oh...

1128
00:43:33,072 --> 00:43:33,072
 

1129
00:43:33,072 --> 00:43:38,014
Yep.  And that time, a buncha guys crashed the party?  Don't you recall that...?

1130
00:43:38,014 --> 00:43:38,054
 

1131
00:43:38,054 --> 00:43:48,042
Well, to be quite frank, since they got wind of a young Tokyo gal being there, they decided to go check her out.  I was one of those fellas.

1132
00:43:48,042 --> 00:43:48,068
 

1133
00:43:48,068 --> 00:43:49,094
Ah, ah...

1134
00:43:49,094 --> 00:43:50,076
 

1135
00:43:50,076 --> 00:43:51,086
That fool!

1136
00:43:51,086 --> 00:44:03,000
 

1137
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:08,050
You came out here to pick benibana?  Are you into dyes or something?

1138
00:44:08,050 --> 00:44:08,052
 

1139
00:44:08,052 --> 00:44:16,090
No, just curious.  You see, benibana are unusual...but maybe not so much for people here.

1140
00:44:16,090 --> 00:44:16,090
 

1141
00:44:16,090 --> 00:44:25,020
Nah.  What's famous is just the name of the cosmetics made from it, but it ain't so common anymore.  Like my farm doesn't make it these days, for one example.

1142
00:44:25,020 --> 00:44:25,022
 

1143
00:44:25,022 --> 00:44:27,030
But I heard it prospered during the Edo era.

1144
00:44:27,030 --> 00:44:27,032
 

1145
00:44:27,032 --> 00:44:34,028
True, 'cause there was a politician who gained influence through its sales.  It would've been a big deal for the wealthier people, but it was only a product as far as we peasants were concerned.

1146
00:44:34,028 --> 00:44:36,096
 

1147
00:44:36,096 --> 00:44:38,024
Ummm...

1148
00:44:38,024 --> 00:44:38,032
 

1149
00:44:38,032 --> 00:44:42,090
``In the end,/Someone else's skin would be touched by/The vermillion flower.'' Do you know this one?

1150
00:44:42,090 --> 00:44:42,092
 

1151
00:44:42,092 --> 00:44:46,064
Right, its a haiku by Basho {<Matsuo Basho>}, right?  I had looked it up before I came here.

1152
00:44:46,064 --> 00:44:46,064
 

1153
00:44:46,064 --> 00:44:51,096
Do tell?  Well, honestly, I looked it up myself yesterday.

1154
00:44:51,096 --> 00:44:51,098
 

1155
00:44:51,098 --> 00:44:54,052
Really...

1156
00:44:54,052 --> 00:44:55,022
 

1157
00:44:55,022 --> 00:45:03,058
That same book also said that the women who gathered the flowers never were able to wear the lipstick made from them.

1158
00:45:03,058 --> 00:45:13,040
 

1159
00:45:13,040 --> 00:45:15,038
Is there going to be a festival here?

1160
00:45:15,038 --> 00:45:15,040
 

1161
00:45:15,040 --> 00:45:18,050
Yep, the riverbank'll be full of people.

1162
00:45:18,050 --> 00:45:30,004
 

1163
00:45:30,004 --> 00:45:34,022
Agriculture's still in trouble, isn't it, with fields being reduced to make way for markets, and such.

1164
00:45:34,022 --> 00:45:34,024
 

1165
00:45:34,024 --> 00:45:42,020
Sure, already there's a lot of trouble, and if it goes on, Japanese agriculture'll be ruined.  Just some day, suddenly ``poof,'' and it's gone.

1166
00:45:42,020 --> 00:45:42,072
 

1167
00:45:42,072 --> 00:45:51,062
But y'know, even with all this trouble or not, if you're trying your best, it still doesn't come easy.  The work in the big city must be the same, right?

1168
00:45:51,062 --> 00:45:52,062
 

1169
00:45:52,062 --> 00:45:57,056
Sure...but the people who think work is everything are becoming fewer in number.

1170
00:45:57,056 --> 00:45:58,074
 

1171
00:45:58,074 --> 00:46:00,050
How 'bout you, Taeko-san [Taeko]?

1172
00:46:00,050 --> 00:46:00,052
 

1173
00:46:00,052 --> 00:46:02,064
Huh?  Me?

1174
00:46:02,064 --> 00:46:04,094
 

1175
00:46:04,094 --> 00:46:10,002
I don't think I'm obsessed...with work, but I don't hate it, either.

1176
00:46:10,002 --> 00:46:12,004
 

1177
00:46:12,004 --> 00:46:18,058
As for me, well, I think I can do my best in agriculture, 'cause its so interesting to raise living things.

1178
00:46:18,058 --> 00:46:19,080
 

1179
00:46:19,080 --> 00:46:21,082
You...raise livestock?

1180
00:46:21,082 --> 00:46:21,084
 

1181
00:46:21,084 --> 00:46:23,004
Huh?

1182
00:46:23,004 --> 00:46:23,086
 

1183
00:46:23,086 --> 00:46:33,071
No, that's not what I meant.  I do have cows and chickens, but I don't mean livestock.  Hey, look there...rice, as well as apples and cherries, they're all living things.

1184
00:46:33,071 --> 00:46:34,044
 

1185
00:46:34,044 --> 00:46:35,022
Ohh.

1186
00:46:35,022 --> 00:46:35,044
 

1187
00:46:35,044 --> 00:46:41,096
Yep.  If I take care of them the best I can, I feel like they respond to me by trying to grow up their best.

1188
00:46:41,096 --> 00:46:44,082
 

1189
00:46:44,082 --> 00:46:48,036
I guess I'm sounding a bit like some hotshot farmer, huh?

1190
00:46:48,036 --> 00:46:48,052
 

1191
00:46:48,052 --> 00:46:51,052
Not at all...I feel I understand.

1192
00:46:51,052 --> 00:46:52,012
 

1193
00:46:52,012 --> 00:46:57,080
To be frank, I was working at a company until recently.  I'm really just a beginning farmer, so...

1194
00:46:57,080 --> 00:46:59,058
 

1195
00:46:59,058 --> 00:47:02,012
Oh...is that so?

1196
00:47:02,012 --> 00:47:02,078
 

1197
00:47:02,078 --> 00:47:07,068
So y'know, with my parents still in good health, maybe that's why my attitude is positive.   But that's how I have to be, you see?

1198
00:47:07,068 --> 00:47:09,074
 

1199
00:47:09,074 --> 00:47:16,030
I quit the company because someone doing ``organic farming'' called me and asked me to try it, too.  Everyone said I was a fool, but so far, I have no regrets.

1200
00:47:16,030 --> 00:47:17,036
 

1201
00:47:17,036 --> 00:47:19,004
``Organic farming?''

1202
00:47:19,004 --> 00:47:21,020
 

1203
00:47:21,020 --> 00:47:27,062
``Farming that requires guts...farming that gives you guts.'' That's a little joke.

1204
00:47:27,062 --> 00:47:28,046
 

1205
00:47:28,046 --> 00:47:34,088
An ``organic farm'' uses as much compost as possible and as few agricultural chemicals and chemical fertilizers as possible.

1206
00:47:34,088 --> 00:47:35,018
 

1207
00:47:35,018 --> 00:47:38,076
Ohh, I've heard about this, it's non-chemical or uses few chemicals.

1208
00:47:38,076 --> 00:47:38,076
 

1209
00:47:38,076 --> 00:47:42,019
But that's not right, it sounds so negative.

1210
00:47:42,019 --> 00:47:42,082
 

1211
00:47:42,082 --> 00:47:50,040
It's really an ideal agriculture that takes advantage of the life force of living things.  And people are only beneficial to it.  That's what makes the whole idea so cool.

1212
00:47:50,040 --> 00:47:51,012
 

1213
00:47:51,012 --> 00:47:51,078
Huh.

1214
00:47:51,078 --> 00:47:53,024
 

1215
00:47:53,024 --> 00:47:56,060
But this ``helping'' part is extremely hard.

1216
00:47:56,060 --> 00:48:04,020
 

1217
00:48:04,020 --> 00:48:06,084
Well, I've been told to take you directly to the fields...

1218
00:48:06,084 --> 00:48:07,004
 

1219
00:48:07,004 --> 00:48:08,070
Right, I'm ready to help out.

1220
00:48:08,070 --> 00:48:09,018
 

1221
00:48:09,018 --> 00:48:11,044
Oh?  You're not going to sleep?

1222
00:48:11,044 --> 00:48:11,090
 

1223
00:48:11,090 --> 00:48:17,004
You see, I heard that benibana should be picked in the early morning, when the dew makes the thorns soft.

1224
00:48:17,004 --> 00:48:17,004
 

1225
00:48:17,004 --> 00:48:18,054
Well, that's true, but...

1226
00:48:18,054 --> 00:48:18,054
 

1227
00:48:18,054 --> 00:48:24,096
I'm a night owl, so I thought the best way to switch my life to being a morning person is to come by a night train.

1228
00:48:24,096 --> 00:48:25,016
 

1229
00:48:25,016 --> 00:48:27,074
Huh, you really get into it, huh?

1230
00:48:27,074 --> 00:48:55,086
 

1231
00:48:55,086 --> 00:48:56,040
There it is!

1232
00:48:56,040 --> 00:49:55,002
 

1233
00:49:55,002 --> 00:49:56,088
Good morning!

1234
00:49:56,088 --> 00:50:06,060
 

1235
00:50:06,060 --> 00:50:08,090
Taeko-san, welcome back!

1236
00:50:08,090 --> 00:50:08,092
 

1237
00:50:08,092 --> 00:50:10,034
Once again, I'm in your debt.

1238
00:50:10,034 --> 00:50:12,054
 

1239
00:50:12,054 --> 00:50:15,090
Obaa-chan, its good to see you doing well.

1240
00:50:15,090 --> 00:50:16,060
 

1241
00:50:16,060 --> 00:50:19,012
Welcome, welcome.

1242
00:50:19,012 --> 00:50:19,014
 

1243
00:50:19,014 --> 00:50:20,010
Aren't you tired?

1244
00:50:20,010 --> 00:50:20,044
 

1245
00:50:20,044 --> 00:50:22,072
No, not at all.

1246
00:50:22,072 --> 00:50:23,002
 

1247
00:50:23,002 --> 00:50:25,064
I made your bed for you just in case...

1248
00:50:25,064 --> 00:50:25,098
 

1249
00:50:25,098 --> 00:50:29,004
I'm fine, look--I'm full of energy!

1250
00:50:29,004 --> 00:50:29,042
 

1251
00:50:29,042 --> 00:50:33,082
Wow, you really are ready--you're wearing a farming uniform.

1252
00:50:33,082 --> 00:50:34,052
 

1253
00:50:34,052 --> 00:50:36,088
Though this is all I'm prepared for.

1254
00:50:36,088 --> 00:50:37,050
 

1255
00:50:37,050 --> 00:50:45,086
Young farmers' wives seldom wear them these days.  But Taeko-san, you're more into it.

1256
00:50:45,086 --> 00:50:46,014
 

1257
00:50:46,014 --> 00:50:47,098
Ain't that a fact.

1258
00:50:47,098 --> 00:51:11,044
 

1259
00:51:11,044 --> 00:51:12,062
Taeko-san!

1260
00:51:12,062 --> 00:51:14,064
 

1261
00:51:14,064 --> 00:51:16,000
Quit that!

1262
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:21,050
 

1263
00:51:21,050 --> 00:51:24,086
And thus began my second experience with country life.

1264
00:51:24,086 --> 00:51:34,058
 

1265
00:51:34,058 --> 00:51:39,042
How can such a vivid crimson color be born from this flower?

1266
00:51:39,042 --> 00:51:40,074
 

1267
00:51:40,074 --> 00:51:43,070
Kiyoko 'ne-san [my sister-in-law, Kiyoko] once told me a sad story that goes with it.

1268
00:51:43,070 --> 00:51:44,082
 

1269
00:51:44,082 --> 00:51:47,012
Long ago, there were no such things as rubber gloves.

1270
00:51:47,012 --> 00:51:48,000
 

1271
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:57,022
When the young girls picked the flowers with their bare hands, they were pricked by the thorns and bled.  The blood turned the color deeper crimson.

1272
00:51:57,022 --> 00:51:58,098
 

1273
00:51:58,098 --> 00:52:07,074
I felt as if I heard the hostile feeling the girls, who never got to put the red color on their lips, must have had against the women in Kyoto that wore it.

1274
00:52:07,074 --> 00:52:09,068
 

1275
00:52:09,068 --> 00:52:19,078
In order to get a handful of rouge, 60 heads of flowers are necessary. That shining, iridescent color had the same value as gold back then, I've heard.

1276
00:52:19,078 --> 00:53:46,094
 

1277
00:53:46,094 --> 00:53:55,056
After washing them with water and stamping on them, kneading them by hand, and letting them sit in the air and water, they become oxidized, and begin to get closer to red in color.

1278
00:53:55,056 --> 00:53:59,046
 

1279
00:53:59,046 --> 00:54:05,028
In addition to that, if you let it sit two or three more days, the flower will ferment, becoming sticky, and turn into a deep red.

1280
00:54:05,028 --> 00:54:08,080
 

1281
00:54:08,080 --> 00:54:17,098
Next, you stamp it with a mortar, squeeze it, and shape it into balls. And if you dry it in an oven, you finally are done with the flower patty, from which the main ingredient of rouge is made.

1282
00:54:17,098 --> 00:54:23,032
 

1283
00:54:23,032 --> 00:54:26,056
A long time ago they didn't waste the remaining water which we got from compressing it earlier.  Now this by-product usually goes unsaved.

1284
00:54:26,056 --> 00:54:26,099
 

1285
00:54:26,099 --> 00:54:33,034
The crimson color, which is still in the leftover water, could be used for making a dye, which cloth can be stained in.  This is the "benibana-dye."

1286
00:54:33,034 --> 00:54:33,076
 

1287
00:54:33,076 --> 00:54:37,010
Be dyed!  Be dyed!/It's benibana-dye!

1288
00:54:37,010 --> 00:54:37,010
 

1289
00:54:37,010 --> 00:54:40,071
Nice colors dye well--Nice colors make my heart brave.

1290
00:54:40,071 --> 00:54:41,052
 

1291
00:54:41,052 --> 00:54:49,066
It's said that the village women, who were denied the rouge or bright kimonos, used to add color to their simple lives by using the benibana-dye.

1292
00:54:49,066 --> 00:54:54,010
 

1293
00:54:54,010 --> 00:54:59,056
The remaining yellow color dissolves in water, and the cotton or hemp is dyed with a beautiful light rouge color.

1294
00:54:59,056 --> 00:55:00,016
 

1295
00:55:00,016 --> 00:55:01,036
Oh, pretty!

1296
00:55:01,036 --> 00:55:03,070
 

1297
00:55:03,070 --> 00:55:12,056
Although a little time and labor has been cut these days, by using machines for example, every day they repeat the work of harvesting the flowers.

1298
00:55:12,056 --> 00:55:40,024
 

1299
00:55:40,024 --> 00:55:44,040
The flower-patties get moldy easily, so precise timing when harvesting the flowers is necessary, for they never wait.

1300
00:55:44,040 --> 00:55:45,044
 

1301
00:55:45,044 --> 00:55:50,090
If you turn around after you've finally finished picking the flowers, you'll see that other new flowers have emerged in the meantime.

1302
00:55:50,090 --> 00:55:54,022
 

1303
00:55:54,022 --> 00:55:59,022
The rainy season comes without mercy, and sometimes work can continue until midnight.

1304
00:55:59,022 --> 00:56:02,008
 

1305
00:56:02,008 --> 00:56:09,096
Day after day passed in the blink of an eye and as I comfortably became tired, I wondered about the women flower harvesters and their conditions.

1306
00:56:09,096 --> 00:56:12,022
 

1307
00:56:12,022 --> 00:56:20,076
If I had a chance to help with such things during my childhood, I surely would have been able to write more lively compositions than my book reports.

1308
00:56:20,076 --> 00:56:37,046
 

1309
00:56:37,046 --> 00:56:39,026
Hey, mom, lemme have 5000 yen<around $30 in 1982>.

1310
00:56:39,026 --> 00:56:39,028
 

1311
00:56:39,028 --> 00:56:41,064
5000 yen?  We don't have that kind of extra money.

1312
00:56:41,064 --> 00:56:41,082
 

1313
00:56:41,082 --> 00:56:45,010
You said you'd buy me a new pair of sports shoes, didn'tcha?

1314
00:56:45,010 --> 00:56:45,030
 

1315
00:56:45,030 --> 00:56:47,072
Are sport shoes so expensive?

1316
00:56:47,072 --> 00:56:47,074
 

1317
00:56:47,074 --> 00:56:48,066
Yep.

1318
00:56:48,066 --> 00:56:48,066
 

1319
00:56:48,066 --> 00:56:49,082
I don't buy that.

1320
00:56:49,082 --> 00:56:49,084
 

1321
00:56:49,084 --> 00:56:50,098
`Cause they're PUMAs.

1322
00:56:50,098 --> 00:56:51,000
 

1323
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:52,040
PUMA?

1324
00:56:52,040 --> 00:56:52,042
 

1325
00:56:52,042 --> 00:56:53,086
Yep, Pu...ma!

1326
00:56:53,086 --> 00:56:56,022
 

1327
00:56:56,022 --> 00:57:00,058
I don't know anything about Pumas, but I DO know you can find ones for cheaper.

1328
00:57:00,058 --> 00:57:00,098
 

1329
00:57:00,098 --> 00:57:02,092
Like how about the same kind you have now?

1330
00:57:02,092 --> 00:57:02,094
 

1331
00:57:02,094 --> 00:57:05,056
No one's wearing boring shoes like them anymore.

1332
00:57:05,056 --> 00:57:05,076
 

1333
00:57:05,076 --> 00:57:08,072
Everybody's getting Puma sports shoes.

1334
00:57:08,072 --> 00:57:08,072
 

1335
00:57:08,072 --> 00:57:09,092
Who's everybody?

1336
00:57:09,092 --> 00:57:09,094
 

1337
00:57:09,094 --> 00:57:13,084
Kako-chan an' Megu-chan, an' also Ya-chan n' Non-chan.

1338
00:57:13,084 --> 00:57:13,084
 

1339
00:57:13,084 --> 00:57:16,056
See, only four people, right?

1340
00:57:16,056 --> 00:57:16,086
 

1341
00:57:16,086 --> 00:57:19,066
I know others--everyone's buying them.

1342
00:57:19,066 --> 00:57:20,008
 

1343
00:57:20,008 --> 00:57:23,042
Nope, you can't ask for that anyway when you're not helping with the chores enough.

1344
00:57:23,042 --> 00:57:23,066
 

1345
00:57:23,066 --> 00:57:26,021
Hey, you got another dress for "Barbie-san" {*} ["Barbie"], didn't you-

1346
00:57:26,021 --> 00:57:26,026
 

1347
00:57:26,026 --> 00:57:32,050
-though you promised to ask for presents only on your birthday and Christmas--and you must have at least known it wasn't your birthday, right?!

1348
00:57:32,050 --> 00:57:33,054
 

1349
00:57:33,054 --> 00:57:35,094
I can't believe Dad's so soft on Taeko!

1350
00:57:35,094 --> 00:57:35,094
 

1351
00:57:35,094 --> 00:57:38,050
Did you promise that, "Ta-bo"<nickname>?

1352
00:57:38,050 --> 00:57:38,094
 

1353
00:57:38,094 --> 00:57:42,054
Unexpectedly, my fifth-grade self emerged yet again.

1354
00:57:42,054 --> 00:57:43,022
 

1355
00:57:43,022 --> 00:57:50,008
But...you bought Yaeko 'ne-chan a long-sleeved kimono, didn't you?  Even though it wasn't even an Adult Celebration day.

1356
00:57:50,008 --> 00:57:50,046
 

1357
00:57:50,046 --> 00:57:51,088
That was for my tea ceremony.

1358
00:57:51,088 --> 00:57:52,004
 

1359
00:57:52,004 --> 00:57:58,064
Well, we see you get a lot of little things all the time, while we get something big only once in a while...right?

1360
00:57:58,064 --> 00:57:58,066
 

1361
00:57:58,066 --> 00:57:59,052
Right!

1362
00:57:59,052 --> 00:58:04,044
 

1363
00:58:04,044 --> 00:58:08,064
Would you stop that...picking only the food you like?!

1364
00:58:08,064 --> 00:58:10,032
 

1365
00:58:10,032 --> 00:58:12,032
Daddy, you like onions, don't you.

1366
00:58:12,032 --> 00:58:12,086
 

1367
00:58:12,086 --> 00:58:13,082
Uh-huh.

1368
00:58:13,082 --> 00:58:14,090
 

1369
00:58:14,090 --> 00:58:19,000
Well, as for the long-sleeved kimono, eventually that dress will be yours anyway, so don't complain.

1370
00:58:19,000 --> 00:58:19,078
 

1371
00:58:19,078 --> 00:58:21,042
``Hand-me-downs''...oh gee.

1372
00:58:21,042 --> 00:58:21,068
 

1373
00:58:21,068 --> 00:58:24,000
Well, some girls don't even get ``hand-me-downs''.

1374
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:24,012
 

1375
00:58:24,012 --> 00:58:25,038
True, true.

1376
00:58:25,038 --> 00:58:25,058
 

1377
00:58:25,058 --> 00:58:28,030
Then give me that enamel bag<purse>of yours soon.

1378
00:58:28,030 --> 00:58:28,032
 

1379
00:58:28,032 --> 00:58:30,008
Oh, didn't you give it to her yet?

1380
00:58:30,008 --> 00:58:30,030
 

1381
00:58:30,030 --> 00:58:34,000
What a baby! The sooner you give it to Taeko, the better.

1382
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:42,019
 

1383
00:58:42,019 --> 00:58:43,034
I don't want it.

1384
00:58:43,034 --> 00:58:44,065
 

1385
00:58:44,065 --> 00:58:46,052
That handbag, I don't want it...

1386
00:58:46,052 --> 00:58:49,034
 

1387
00:58:49,034 --> 00:58:51,016
Oh, really?  That's fine, then I won't give it to you.

1388
00:58:51,016 --> 00:58:52,018
 

1389
00:58:52,018 --> 00:58:54,006
I won't be buying a new one.

1390
00:58:54,006 --> 00:58:54,028
 

1391
00:58:54,028 --> 00:58:55,034
Fine by me!

1392
00:58:55,034 --> 00:58:56,006
 

1393
00:58:56,006 --> 00:58:59,048
Whew, that's good.  That bag was a favorite of mine, anyway.

1394
00:58:59,048 --> 00:59:00,000
 

1395
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:01,062
I totally hate that one!

1396
00:59:01,062 --> 00:59:05,074
 

1397
00:59:05,074 --> 00:59:08,086
Hey, I'm ready.  Could you take care of this?

1398
00:59:08,086 --> 00:59:08,099
 

1399
00:59:08,099 --> 00:59:11,040
See--and the food gets thrown away anyway.

1400
00:59:11,040 --> 00:59:11,048
 

1401
00:59:11,048 --> 00:59:13,012
Wasteful, isn't she?

1402
00:59:13,012 --> 00:59:14,086
 

1403
00:59:14,086 --> 00:59:17,005
No, don't throw it away! Hey, Mother...!

1404
00:59:17,005 --> 00:59:17,036
 

1405
00:59:17,036 --> 00:59:20,096
You picked these out, didn't you? If you're going to complain now, then you should have eaten all the food on your plate.

1406
00:59:20,096 --> 00:59:23,031
 

1407
00:59:23,031 --> 00:59:26,011
All of my kids are so selfish.

1408
00:59:26,011 --> 00:59:36,011
 

